JND for Brightness

Weberâ€™s Law:

\[ JND = \Delta I = Change\;in\;Intensity \]

\[ k = \frac{\Delta I}{I} = \frac{JND\;(Change\;in\;Intensity)}{Original\; Intensity} \]

k is some constant. This means that the bigger the original intensity, the bigger the increase needs to be to detect a change.

In other words, itâ€™s the ratio of intensities that matters.

Weberâ€™s Law holds for most perceptual phenomena, including visual, aural, tactile, etc., but each has itâ€™s own value k. Perception in general is logarithmic (depends on ratios).

For Brightness (Intensity of Light), k = 0.08

For Loudenss (Intensity of Sound), k = 0.05

JND for Brightness

Weberâ€™s Law:

So,

\[ 0.08 = \frac{\Delta I}{I} = \frac{JND\;(Change\;in\;Brightness)}{Original\; Brightness} \]

So, to find the smallest perceivable difference in brightness, you can multiply the original by 0.08 (if you have a light meter).

PROBLEM: You canâ€™t do that with normal RGB, CMYK or Hex color values! Those color spaces are lonlinear, and so is our perception, but in different ways. So you canâ€™t just multiply. You can only multiply light intensity values measured with a light meter!

SOLUTION: Use a “perceptually uniform” colorspace (like CIE-LAB), which has been designed based on empirical study of human perception.

Tools exist to automatically generate perceptually uniform color and brightness scales, and color pallets. The best visualization software has these scales or tools built in.

Stevensâ€™ Power Law

Psychophysics is the quantitative description of the relationship between physical stimuli and perception (response).

\(\psi(I) = kI^\alpha\)

Stevensâ€™ Power Law describes the subjective response \(\psi\) to the magnitude of physical stimulus \(I\).

Stevens fit power laws as a first approximation to experimental data.

Data were collected by asking subjects to provide subjective ratios in response to pairs of stimuli.
Subsequent researchers come up with different values of \(\alpha\).
Responses are highly subjective for some stimuli.
Wilkinson has a good discussion in Grammar of Graphics.

Stevens, S. S. (1957). On the psychophysical law. Psychological Review, 64(3), 153-181: http://dx.doi.org/10.1037/h0046162

Take-away:

“Length” is the only visual parameter with 1:1 linear perceptual response curve, soâ€¦

  1. plot your most important variables using length (or x y position) in 2D
    (line charts, bar charts, scatterplots, etc.)

  2. Reserve other visual parameters (color, area, etc.) for less important variables

  3. When not using length, use perceptually uniform scales (mostly applies to color)

  4. Best mappings depend on the nature of the data (Quantitative, Ordinal, Nominal)

Pre-attentive processing = unconscious imformation processing

  • The brain first pre-processes all the information in a scene unconsciously.
  • The most salient information is passed on for conscious (attentive) processing.

Salient Information is information that:

  • stands out the most (“pops”), or
  • is relevant to what a person is thinking about

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pre-attentive_processing

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Feature_integration_theory

Gestalt: “shape or form” (German)

Gestalt Theory tries to explain how our brain generates mental perceptions of whole forms out of incomplete or chaotic stimulus.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gestalt_psychology

Principles

Emergence: Recognition occurs all at once, holistically. (We donâ€™t build up a percept or mental image of an object consciously.)
Reification: The percept (mental image) can contains more information than the stimuli on which it is based. (We fill in missing pieces of a whole.)
Multistability: Ambiguous perceptual experiences pop back and forth between interpretations. (We donâ€™t know why.)
Invariance: Simple geometrical objects are recognized independent of rotation, translation, scale and several other variations.
